Part 1: Hypothesis for Average Sale Value of Movies

Formulate Hypotheses

  • Null Hypothesis (H0H_0H0​): The average sale value of movies is at least 100 million dollars. H0:μ≥100H_0: \mu \geq 100H0​:μ≥100
  • Alternative Hypothesis (HAH_AHA​): The average sale value of movies is less than 100 million dollars. HA:μ<100H_A: \mu < 100HA​:μ<100

Conditions for Conducting a Z-Test

  1. Normality: The movie sale values should be normally distributed or the sample size should be sufficiently large (n≥30n \geq 30n≥30) for the Central Limit Theorem to apply.
  2. Independence: The movie sales data should be independently sampled.
  3. Known Population Standard Deviation (σ\sigmaσ): A z-test requires the population standard deviation to be known. If unknown, a t-test should be used instead.

Part 2: Steps to Validate the Board Member's Opinion on Comedy vs. Action Movie Profits

Step 1: Define Hypotheses

  • Null Hypothesis (H0H_0H0​): The average profit of Comedy movies is equal to or greater than that of Action movies. H0:μC≥μAH_0: \mu_C \geq \mu_AH0​:μC​≥μA​
  • Alternative Hypothesis (HAH_AHA​): The average profit of Comedy movies is lower than that of Action movies. HA:μC<μAH_A: \mu_C < \mu_AHA​:μC​<μA​

  • Gather profit data for Comedy and Action genre movies.
  • Ensure a sufficiently large and representative sample.

Step 3: Choose the Appropriate Test

  • If population standard deviations are known, use a two-sample z-test for mean comparison.
  • If population standard deviations are unknown, use a two-sample t-test (assuming normality or large enough sample size).

  • Use the test statistic formula for two independent samples: t=XˉC−XˉAsC2nC+sA2nAt = \frac{\bar{X}_C - \bar{X}_A}{\sqrt{\frac{s_C^2}{n_C} + \frac{s_A^2}{n_A}}}t=nC​sC2​​+nA​sA2​​​XˉC​−XˉA​​ where XˉC,XˉA\bar{X}_C, \bar{X}_AXˉC​,XˉA​ are the sample means, sC,sAs_C, s_AsC​,sA​ are the sample standard deviations, and nC,nAn_C, n_AnC​,nA​ are the sample sizes.
